gland":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Woolley, Yorkshire, England":"Woolley, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wollay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Lancashire): variant of the Devon surname <b>Woolland</b>, perhaps a habitational name from Woolland in Dorset, named from Old English <i>wynne</i> ‘pasture, meadow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’. Alternatively, but less likely, a topographic name from Middle English <i>wough</i> ‘bent, crooked’ + <i>land(e)</i>, <i>lond(e)</i> ‘land’ (Old English <i>wōh</i> + <i>land</i>), perhaps denoting a person who lived at or near a bend in a stream or river, or for someone from any place so named, such as Wollensbrook in Great Amwell (Hertfordshire). This surname is rare in Britain.","Americanized form of German   Ulm  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wollan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard.","English (Staffordshire and Somerset): variant of   Wollam  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads, mainly in Trøndelag, named <i>Vollan</i>, from the definite plural form of   Voll   (‘meadow’). Compare   Wollen  ."]},{"name":"Woolam","meanings":["English: variant of   Wollam  .","Americanized form of German   Ulm  ."]},{"name":"Ulm","meanings":["German:","habitational name from the city of this name in Baden-Württemberg. The placename is from the root <i>uel</i>, an unattested word meaning ‘turn, wind, roll’, or from <i>el-</i> or <i>ol-</i> ‘flow’, a reference in either case to the influx of the Blan river into the Danube.","from a short form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Odolmar</i> (see   Ulmer   2). Compare   Ollom  ,   Ullom  ,   Ullum  ,   Wollam  , and   Woolam  ."]},{"name":"Woolen","meanings":["English: variant of   Wollam  . In northern England, the surname is unexplained."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":59,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":90,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1